<subSubSection pageId="82" pageNumber="83" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="82.[151,1437,597,1892]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1829,1855]" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[597,710,1829,1854]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="82" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scordalus">
<emphasis box="[597,710,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="82" pageNumber="83">scordalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a Latin noun meaning quarrelsome devil, refers to the robust appearance of the one known specimen of this species.
</paragraph>
